<section xml:id="s_limits">
  <title>Limits of functions</title>

</introduction>
  <definition xml:id="d_limits_two_sided_limit">
    <title>Limit at a point</title>
    <idx><h>limit</h></idx>
    <statement>
      <p>
      Let <m>f</m> be a real-valued function with domain <m>D \subseteq \mathbb{R}</m>, and suppose <m>D</m> contains a punctured interval about <m>c \in \mathbb{R}</m>. We say <term>the limit of <m>f(x)</m> as <m>x</m> approaches <m>c</m> exists </m></term> if there is an <m>L \in \mathbb{R}</m> satisfying the following condition: for every <m>\epsilon>0</m> there exists a <m>\delta>0</m> such that whenever <m>x \in (c-\delta,c) \cup (c,c+\delta)</m> we have <m>f(x) \in (L-\epsilon,L+\epsilon)</m>.

      Using logical shorthand:
      <men xml:id="d_limit_implication">
        x \in (c-\delta,c) \cup (c,c+\delta) \implies f(x) \in (L-\epsilon,L+\epsilon)
      </men>.

      In this case we call <m>L</m> the <term> limit of <m>f(x)</m> as <m>x</m> approaches <m>c</m> </term>, and write
      <me>
        \lim\limits_{x\to c}f(x)=L
      </me>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <definition xml:id="d_limits_one_sided_limit">
    <title>One-Sided Limits</title>
    <idx><h>one-sided limit</h></idx>
    <statement>
      <p>
      Let <m>f</m> be a real-valued function with domain <m>D</m>, and suppose <m>D</m> contains an interval <m>(c,d)</m>. We say <term>the limit of <m>f(x)</m> as <m>x</m> approaches <m>c</m> from the right exists </m></term> if there is an <m>L \in \mathbb{R}</m> satisfying the following condition: for every <m>\epsilon>0</m> there exists a <m>\delta>0</m> such that whenever <m>x \in (c,c+\delta)</m> we have <m>f(x) \in (L-\epsilon,L+\epsilon)</m>.

      Using logical shorthand:
      <me>
        x \in (c,c+\delta) \implies f(x) \in (L-\epsilon,L+\epsilon)
      </me>.

      In this case we call <m>L</m> the <term> limit of <m>f(x)</m> as <m>x</m> approaches <m>c</m> </term>, and write
      <me>
        \lim\limits_{x\to c^+}f(x)=L
      </me>.

      Similarly, assuming <m>D</m> contains an interval <m>(b,c)</m>, we say <term>the limit of <m>f(x)</m> as <m>x</m> approaches <m>c</m> from the left exists </m></term> if there is an <m>L \in \mathbb{R}</m> satisfying the following condition: for every <m>\epsilon>0</m> there exists a <m>\delta>0</m> such that whenever <m>x \in (c-\delta,c)</m> we have <m>f(x) \in (L-\epsilon,L+\epsilon)</m>.

      Using logical shorthand:
      <me>
        x \in (c-\delta,c) \implies f(x) \in (L-\epsilon,L+\epsilon)
      </me>.

      In this case we call <m>L</m> the <term> limit of <m>f(x)</m> as <m>x</m> approaches <m>c</m> from the left</term>, and write
      <me>
        \lim\limits_{x\to c^-}f(x)=L
      </me>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>


  <definition xml:id="d_limits_limit_at_infinity">
    <title>Limits at Infinity</title>
    <idx><h>limit at infinity</h></idx>
    <statement>
      <p>
      Let <m>f</m> be a real-valued function. We say <term>the limit of <m>f(x)</m> as <m>x</m> approaches infinity exists </m></term> if there is an <m>L \in \mathbb{R}</m> satisfying the following condition: for every <m>\epsilon>0</m> there exists an <m>N>0</m> such that whenever <m>x \in (M, \infty)</m> we have <m>f(x) \in (L-\epsilon,L+\epsilon)</m>.

      Using logical shorthand:
      <me>
        x \in (M, \infinity) \implies f(x) \in (L-\epsilon,L+\epsilon)
      </me>.

      In this case we call <m>L</m> the <term> limit of <m>f(x)</m> as <m>x</m> approaches infinity </term>, and write
      <me>
        \lim\limits_{x\to \infty}f(x)=L
      </me>.

      Similarly, we say <term>the limit of <m>f(x)</m> as <m>x</m> approaches negative infinity exists </m></term> if there is an <m>L \in \mathbb{R}</m> satisfying the following condition: for every <m>\epsilon>0</m> there exists an <m>N</m> such that whenever <m>x \in (-\infty, N)</m> we have <m>f(x) \in (L-\epsilon,L+\epsilon)</m>.

      Using logical shorthand:
      <me>
        x \in (-\infty, N) \implies f(x) \in (L-\epsilon,L+\epsilon)
      </me>.

      In this case we call <m>L</m> the <term> limit of <m>f(x)</m> as <m>x</m> approaches negative infinity </term>, and write
      <me>
        \lim\limits_{x\to -\infty}f(x)=L
      </me>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>


  <definition xml:id="d_limits_infinite_limit">
    <title>Infinite Limits</title>
    <idx><h>infinite limit</h></idx>
    <statement>
      <p>
      Let <m>f</m> be a real-valued function with domain <m>D</m>, and suppose <m>D</m> contains a punctured interval about <m>c \in \mathbb{R}</m>. We say <term><m>f(x)</m> approaches infinity as <m>x</m> approaches <m>c</m></m></term> if the following condition is met: for every <m>N \in \mathbb{R}</m> there exists a <m>\delta>0</m> such that whenever <m>x \in (c-\delta,c) \cup (c,c+\delta)</m> we have <m>f(x) \in (N, \infty)</m>.

      Using logical shorthand:
      <me>
        x \in (c-\delta,c) \cup (c,c+\delta) \implies f(x) \in (N, \infty)
      </me>.

      In this case we write
      <me>
        \lim\limits_{x\to c}f(x)=\infty
      </me>.

      Similarly, we say <term><m>f(x)</m> approaches negative infinity as <m>x</m> approaches <m>c</m></m></term> if the following condition is met: for every <m>N \in \mathbb{R}</m> there exists a <m>\delta>0</m> such that whenever <m>x \in (c-\delta,c) \cup (c,c+\delta)</m> we have <m>f(x) \in (-\infty, N)</m>.

      Using logical shorthand:
      <me>
        x \in (c-\delta,c) \cup (c,c+\delta) \implies f(x) \in (-\infty, N)
      </me>.

      In this case we write
      <me>
        \lim\limits_{x\to c}f(x)=-\infty
      </me>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>
